{"author":{"id":"75732e82453cc4795a3b5d7bef7a9ce916b428e5bbe06161843f7392657be5c1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1445188165,"nonce":"ussAQ9YBa6WfPRswOH8R1ADpadg=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDE0OTAzMTAzMQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/332#issuecomment-149031031"},"message":"\u003e I see it more like we fitting them to other tools, not Galaxy. We all do the same in R and Python if we import data in dataframes, isn't it?\n\nThanks this clearly shows me your point of view.\n\n\u003e And tabular is imho defined tab separated file without metadata.\n\nThis is stated in Tabular.py:\n\n```\n# This is our first line, people seem to like to upload files that have a header line, but do not\n# start with '#' (i.e. all column types would then most likely be detected as str).  We will assume\n# that the first line is always a header (this was previous behavior - it was always skipped).  When\n# the requested skip is None, we only use the data from the first line if we have no other data for\n# a column. ... truncated ...\n```\n\n\u003e Otherwise we need to define these as comment lines.\n\n+1\n\nFrom the text from Tabular.py I also see this as the solution for featureCounts. I want to keep the column names because for large cohorts (once I had to do 96 samples) you loose which column belongs to which sample when you download the file. The very first char of the header columns should be a `#`, which would mark the header line as a comment line. Then DESeq should be written such that it skips comment lines, if it doesn't do this already.\n\n\u003e Why not? It's true we'd need to do this for htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts, but if we decide on a common datatype with common metadata, then we'd only need to map Identifiers and counts in the datatype.\n\nThese file formats do not have a clear specification like e.g. SAM and that makes this tough to achieve. The formats are quite similar (tab delimited, columns with numbers) and therefore it is not easy to write an accurate sniffers for them. They also do not have something like %%FEATURECOUNTS-EXPRESSION-TABLE-v1.4.6. Therefore I think it's an overkill (time and efford) to write a file format for each of these tools.\n\n\u003e  I'm a bit vague here, admittedly, but it would be nice if galaxy tools could transparently handle the native dataformats produced by htseq-count, featureCounts and DEXSeq-counts, since the kind of information they provide is the same.\n\nYou should blame the tool-wrapper authors (in this case it's me) for not having done this. Still this wouldn't solve the issue, because each next tool in the pipeline (edger, deseq, dexseq, ...) should then have a parser for each possible format.  One format to rule them all would be ideal, but that doesn't exist afaik, and would most likely not be a tabular format either.\n\n\u003e Shouldn't be a file type as strictly defined as possible?\n\n+1\n\n\u003e The purpose of this is that tool wrappers that produce counts would set this new datatypes as output format and assign columns and rows of their tabular output data to the correct metadata. Then the datatype would also take care of the conversion, so that tools that need a header-line in their input receive the correct header line, and tools that need multiple input files (one per sample) would receive this as input.\n\nI am not sure if you see this within galaxy or as public tools (like samtools and vcftools) and implement those in galaxy. I think if you start such stuff it also needs indexed access, binary access API etc. available and write a paper on it, otherwise nobody else will use it and we end up with yet another format https://xkcd.com/927/. Other things missing in the current formats are the method used to count (how to treat overlapping annotations and multi-map reads) and the exact genomic structure of each feature counted; it relates to a GTF file which is not explicitly denoted or included.\n\n\u003e Let me know if you think this is nonsense (honesty appreciated!). I'll be pretty busy the next weeks, but I could keep this in my inbox.\n\nIt's not nonsense but it probably is a lot of work! This time could be spend on getting GOSeq working or cairo :P\n\nTo me the most logical way to close this issue is to let DESeq understand comment lines and denote it clearly in the `\u003chelp\u003e` section, because the comment are part of the galaxy specification of a Tabular file. To make other tools (featureCounts) compatible with DESeq we can refer to the specification of a tabular file and the README of DESeq.","files":null}]}